40|$|Reliable {{electronic}} commerce must offer fairness. This dissertation focuses upon realizingfair {{electronic commerce}} for mobile environments such as mobile phone systems; itintroduces protocols and a communication framework {{to implement a}} feasible commerceinfrastructure that allows users to efficiently and fairly trade diverse valuable items suchas <b>electronic</b> <b>rights</b> and digital contents, by effectively using personal tamper-resistantdevices such as UICC (Universal Integrated Circuit Card) smartcards, a common adjunctto 3 rd-generation mobile phones. To make various valuable items including money, tickets, and coupons uniformly tradable,this dissertation introduces the notion of <b>electronic</b> <b>rights,</b> which are the electronicrepresentation of rights to claim some goods or services, and presents a copy preventionscheme to securely realize transferable <b>electronic</b> <b>rights</b> and an optimistic fair exchangeprotocol that enables users to trade such <b>electronic</b> <b>rights</b> fairly and efficiently. Next, anoptimistic fair exchange method based on solving the non-blocking atomic commitment(NBAC) problem is presented to extend the range of tradable items from electronic rightsto arbitrary items including digital contents without sacrificing efficiency. To providea formal proof of the security of such agreement-based fairness, the construction of anideal functionality equivalent to NBAC in the universal composability framework anda formal proof of their equivalence are presented. Finally, a communication frameworkfor the efficient implementation of inter-smartcard distributed protocols is presented. Aprototype system implementing the fair exchange protocol for trading <b>electronic</b> <b>rights</b> onthis framework is evaluated and the results confirm feasibility of the protocol and meritsof the framework. It shows that a feasible mobile electronic commerce infrastructure canbe realized by applying the approaches present